>Moving parts are a weakness after all
I'm surprised more people don't notice this on their own, but think about the tracks on a tank and how many links they're comprised of, how much stress the links are under when the tank moves, and how exposed the links are. Too many moving parts in their motive system is the actually the key weakness of tanks.
Modern tanks have modular hull armor that makes a lot of mid-century AT systems nigh-obsolete, but tank designers can't do anything to protect the parts of their treads that need to be exposed to touch the terrain. Being damaged beyond repair was a lot less common for western tanks in the middle east than getting immobilised, because besides rockets and mines, aggressive manoeuvring can also throw a track.
>>61428839
Dune's shields are pretty interesting because they're defeated by exploiting a gap in the logic they use to determine what is and isn't a threat. The weapons used to bypass a shield are ordinary, but the technique is very difficult to learn because the attacker must have the finesse to strike quickly enough that the opponent cannot parry the blow, but slowly enough that the shield will not activate. It's a difficult balancing act and duels between shielded opponents can be awkwardly drawn out affairs.
